tive Agentic Paradigms -- tChapter Eleven. Ecofeminist Materialism and Entanglements of Care in Sara Mesa’s Un incendio invisible -- tChapter Twelve. Trans-Corporeal Matter Narratives in Hierro -- tChapter Thirteen ¡El toro no entiende de toreo! Taurine Naturecultures, Wenceslao Fernández Flórez’s Anti-Taurine Essays, and the Emergence of Post-Humanist Views of Animals in Spain -- tChapter Fourteen. Ecohorror as Critique of Anthropogenic (Self-)Destruction in Albert Sánchez Piñol’s Cold Skin -- tPART FOUR Medium as Activism Igniter -- tChapter Fifteen. Monstrous Humanity: An Ecopostcolonial Reading of Laura Gallego García’s Trilogy Guardianes de la Ciudadela -- tChapter Sixteen. La cuenta atrás: An Ecodystopian Graphic Novel on Spain’s Greatest Ecological Disaster -- tChapter Seventeen. Drawing Ecological Thought: Anthropomorphism and Satire as Critique of Capitalism in the TwentyFirst-Century Spanish Comic -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aChronicling sixteenth-century Spain to the present day, Beyond Human aims to decentre the human and acknowledge the material historicity of more-than-human nature. The book explores key questions relating to ecological equity, justice, and responsibility within and beyond Spain in the Anthropocene. Examining relations between Iberian cultural practices, historical developments, and ecological processes, Maryanne L. Leone, Shanna Lino, and the contributors to this volume reveal the structures that uphold and dismantle the non-human–human dichotomy and nature-culture divide. The book critiques works from the Golden Age to the twenty-first century in a wide range of genres, including comedia, royal treatises, agricultural reports, paintings, satirical essays, horror fiction and film, young adult and speculative literature, poetry, graphic novels, and television series. The authors contend that Spanish cultural studies must expose the material historicity that entangles today’s ecological crises and ecosocial injustices with previous, future, and contemporary entities. The book argues that this will require the simultaneous decentring of the human and of the Anthropocene as an ecocritical framework. By standardizing ecosocial analysis and widening avenues for ecopedagogical approaches, Beyond Human participates in the ecocentric transformation of Hispanic cultural studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEcocriticismzSpain. 0aEcology in literature. 0aSpanish literaturexHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Spanish & Portuguese.2bisacsh  aAnthropocene.  aCapitalocene.  aHispanic.  aIberian.  aSpain.  aSpanish.  acultural studies.  adegrowth.  aecocriticism.  aecofeminism.  aecology.  aenvironmental culture.  aequity.  amore-than-human.  anatureculture.  anew materialism.  anonhuman.1 aAlmanza-Gálvez, Carla, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAres-López, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeusterien, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrito-Vera, Mª Concepción, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColbert, Olga, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrost, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGalván, Juan Carlos Martín, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGasior, Bonnie L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGonzález-Rodríguez, Mª Luz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKetz, Victoria L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeone, Maryanne L.